cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|No, 2@S.  My philosophy is, there is no gap between 2S and 1@S. With a six card suit, you either have to open 1@S or 2@S.  You cannot pass if not sure. That is just a matter of style. But the point of preempting is higher risk higher reward. However, many experts would pass with your hand, particularly because of your heart suit.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


AT|
IraCT: ok   thanks   I did consider all 3 before bidding and felt I could always come in and bid 2@S.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It is true, that Ira could bid 2@S later. However, the preempt then loses much of its effectiveness, because the opponents have had a chance to communicate. The idea behind a preempt is to disrupt the opponents' communications, and coming in later does not do that as much.|
